The highest-value relationship categories in real banks

If you are building a KG for RBC, BNY, JPMorgan, Goldman Sachs, or State Street, roughly 80% of business value comes from these relationship families:

Trade ↔ Counterparty
Trade ↔ Product
Trade ↔ Position
Position ↔ Price
Position ↔ Risk Factor
Portfolio ↔ Holdings
Security ↔ Issuer
Issuer ↔ Corporate Hierarchy
Trade ↔ Agreement
Trade ↔ Regulatory Obligation
Attribute ↔ Business Term
Attribute ↔ Source System
Report Field ↔ Data Element
Dataset ↔ Downstream Consumer

These relationships enable the most valuable questions:

What exposures do we have to a corporate group?
Which reports are impacted by a bad security price?
Which trades are affected by a corporate action?
Which positions contribute most to VaR?
Which downstream systems use this attribute?
Which regulations apply to this transaction?
Which data elements are required to calculate NAV, ABOR, or IBOR?
What business processes will break if a vendor feed fails?
